Jul 31 2009 	Great Value Fun Property Highly Recommended	When traveling to San Francisco, there really is only one extreme or the other; going on a budget, or going all out. If you're looking for luxury, high-end, and top-of-the line, you are better plunking down that $150+ at a place like the W, Clift, Four Seasons, or Ritz Carlton. If you are looking for great value, but still feel comfortable, safe, and fun, the Good Hotel can not be beat. Granted, the name gets a laugh whenever I tell people I'm staying at the Good Hotel. I arrived by car (was dropped off by a friend), as I needed to spend a night in the city, but did not feel the need to splurge since I was traveling alone. As you'll see other reviews debate, the location is not AMAZING. It's not Union Square, it's not Fisherman's Wharf, but it is SAFE. There are still plenty of restaurants, shops, and attractions nearby, and the area is very populated that you would never feel like you were going to find yourself in a sticky situation. Those that write they were scared of the area or the people apparently grew up very sheltered; no matter where you go in San Francisco, there are homeless, and there are people asking for money. Quite honestly, I had more concerning encounters staying in the Union Square area than I did at the Good Hotel.Having said that, the location is very convenient. It's within two blocks of the Civic Center BART station, which can get you just about anywhere in town very quickly. There are some amazing buildings around the Good Hotel (as close as across the street), and much to admire. Check-in at the Good Hotel was quick and simple. I booked online for a very reasonable rate (under $100), and was given my room keys, and quick run-down of the property, and details on how to work the free wifi. In the lobby is a conveniently located soda machine, snack machine, and a photo booth. For $5 it may be a little pricey to do the photo booth, but a ton of fun! My friend who visited me took photos, and you are given two copies (many guests post their photos in the lobby, and it's fun to see all the different faces).The common area is nicely decorated with colorful sofas and plasma TVs. I was directed to my room by the front desk agent, and was staying in the courtyard area (overlooking the parking lot, which is very convenient if you drive). The room, while not huge, was spacious enough for two people (one bed), and included two nightstands, a dresser, cozy little work area, closet, and bathroom. The flat-screen TV was easy to work, and had a nice selection of channels. The wifi, also, was simple to work, and great for being free. Free tea in the room was a nice touch, and quite honestly, I found the room very cozy and functional for my stay. The bathroom, while tiny, never felt cramped, and the shower had a neat little dispenser for shampoo, conditioner, and shower gel (all nice smelling products).I opted to grab a quick dinner at Good Pizza, connected to the lobby. I was able to get a 9&quot; pizza, drink, and two cookies for under $15. While those eating there looked to be hotel guests (and many appeared to be from other countries), the service was quick, prompt, and FRIENDLY. The pizza was very delicious, too. I was told the restaurant also delivers directly to the room, though I enjoyed eating in the large area. I really enjoyed my dinner, and went for a walk to the BART station around 8:30pm (returned back via bus around 10:00pm). Again, I never felt uncomfortable or threatened in the area, and I'm a very small person traveling alone. I returned to my room and enjoyed eating a snack while overlooking the parking lot (a few other guests in this courtyard were standing out on the walkway having a drink or chatting, and it was a very inviting atmosphere). The property is not loud at all, even for being right on the street (and having a room overlooking the street). Everything at the Good Hotel was great, and the in-room amenities, especially for the price, can not be beat (great AC system, though I wish the remote was not attached to the wall).If you are in San Francisco and looking to travel on a budget, this is a great great choice. Don't let the other reviews about location deter you, enjoy the nice property and convenience, and remember traveling in a big city comes with its share of different people from different cultures. Additionally, take advantage of the lobby area; there were two new iMac computers, with easy to use internet, word processing, and printing. Made a quick look on Google Maps for directions, or e-mail check nice (and fun to use).	
