Jul 12 2009 	Great starting point to enjoy San Francisco	I've never been to San Francisco, but after a lot of reading and a good deal on Orbitz, we decided on the Good Hotel due to its location in the downtown part of the city, thinking it would be fairly central to everything we wanted to see. Arrived from the airport on the BART train with no problem, from the Civic Center Station which I believe is 5th street, it was a short but very colorful walk. There are a lot of bums and homeless looking individuals in the area - people sleeping on the ground, pushing shopping carts filled with stuff, arguing with benches... Initially, I felt very uncomfortable dragging my suitcase to the hotel, I felt like we screamed &quot;target.&quot; However, once I got used to the scene (and dropped off the luggage) I never felt unsafe, but def had an awareness about who was around me at all times. There are all kinds of shops - liquor stores, delis, pawn shops, strip clubs, fast food - in the area between 7th and 4th. Once you hit 4th and on up to 3rd, its a different vibe...lots of shopping and tourists, street performers, restaurants, etc. My husband said it was like a needle skipping off a record once you crossed over to 4th st heading to 5th, haha!The Good Hotel itself is very cool. The lobby always had a friendly and helpful person out front. There is a space for lounging in the lobby, with 3 TVs to watch, but they seemed to play the same DVDs over and over again - some sort of sea life show, another I can't remember, and Puppy Party, which is a show featuring cute puppies frolicking...and that's all it's about....all puppies, all the time. There is a picture booth to take your photo and post on a communal cork board, showing other visitors who have stayed. The age of people at the hotel was varied from young singles and backpackers to older travelers to couples and people with families. Internet access is available for a charge, 2 nice Macs in the lobby. There is a smoking patio out back of the lobby, and it seemed a to be a gathering place for a lot of folks.The hotel - lobby, hallways, rooms - is painted very neat. Lots of blues, yellows and greens, and everything was very clean. You can tell the building is old, but a lot of time has been spent remodeling to give it a very hip feel. The hotel uses recycled/reclaimed materials as much as possible.Our room had 2 twin beds, which may seem unusual as a couple, but it was the best price. In room iron, tea/coffee set, safe, writing desk, a bin for recycling. The shower and toilet are together, it's a small space, but it works. There was a retractable clothing line in the shower for hanging laundry if needed. And there are soap/shampoo/conditioner dispensers in shower. The toilet has a small basin and spigot on the back. It took us a bit to figure it out, but I think the purpose is....after you flush, the toilet tank fills with clean water...the clean water comes out of the spigot, you can wash your hands, then the water drains from the basin into the tank to fill the toilet, getting 2 uses out of one round of water. That is our best guess anyway, haha! The actual sink and faucet are outside the bathroom, in the sleeping area. Some other reviews mentioned that they didn't like that, but it was no big deal to us. The beds were comfortable and had several comfy pillows on them. There was a flatscreen TV with cable and in-room movies available. We were on the 3rd floor. We left the bathroom window open at night for some cool air, and was never bothered by street noise. Our second day there, the person next to us had a dog in her room, which we heard barking in the morning, but it was not too loud. Overall, the room reminded me of a dorm in its layout and space, but it was so much more than that thanks to a hip look and laid back atmosphere.There is a restaurant attached through the lobby, Good Pizza. We did not try it as we saw someone sneeze and not wash her hands, and then turn around and serve food. We did cross the street to a sister hotel, the Americania Hotel, and enjoyed a fantastic burger at Custom Burger. The Americania also has a very cool bar, with service that was excellent. Glad we found it, after sightseeing all day and a dodgy neighborhood at night, it was but a 30 second walk to get a cocktail. Hopping a bus or trolley was no problem, and all major sites were no more than 15 minutes away. Use the public transport system, it's cheaper, efficient and you will meet some very interesting people. We met an opera singer, that doesn't happen in a taxi.San Francisco is a fantastic city, and the Good Hotel is great starting point to enjoy it!	
Jul 10 2009 	Great value unique eco-freindly/trendy in SOMA	I was referred to this hotel by a friend that stayed there a few years back with it was the Brighton. Its been fully upgraded with trendy basics. It's not the Ritz but for the money a comfortable value. The company that owns this, JDV has several other properties in the area including two Best Westerns on the same street and pride them selves as being a great corporate citizen which they achieve. This hotel is dedicated to volunteerism and I applaud their efforts. &quot;Good&quot; as in good for the environment, the body, the soul and diversity. The rooms are of average size, nice bathrooms, while not luxurious; they are big enough to turn around in with bumping into something. Environmentally friendly amenities, in room safe, Ikea style furnishings. The inscription on the wall says &quot;be good&quot; and on the ceiling when you go to bed there a glow in the dark &quot;good night&quot; to send you on to sweet dreams. Staff is friendly and helpful, my only very minor complaint is that the housekeepers make the beds military tight, you could bounce a quarter off of them but for a tall guy that wants to be fully covered its a chore getting the covers to loosen up. With a rate of less than $80 plus tax, parking is $22 (free if your driving a hybrid), this is a value. The neighborhood can be a little iffy at night as it's close to the tenderloin and there are a lot of homeless and panhandlers. There are some good restaurants for dinner down on Folsom, just a few blocks away. Breakfast and Lunch can be a little more difficult. The &quot;Good&quot; Restaurant in the hotel was not that &quot;good&quot; - the pzza was less than what I would expect out of the supermarket frozen section, also unkept and the tables were all dirty.	
