Apr 21 2009 	Incredible Value in San Francisco!	I stayed at the Good Hotel for four nights in April. I booked through the Joie de Vivre website (this is a part of the JDV chain) and got a spring special: 30% off a stay of 4 nights or more. JDV often offers this type of special, so it's useful to check their website when booking.The hotel is very conveniently located at 7th and Mission, literally one block from the Civic Center BART station 7th Street entrance. I took BART from the airport and walked less on the street from BART than I had walked within the airport to get to BART. I was also able to use BART and MUNI for all my movement, so never had to rent a car. I also love the SOMA (South of Market) neighborhood - I know that people have commented on the homeless, the noise and the general feel of the are. What many visitors don't understand is what an incredibly vibrant neighborhood this is - with the gourmet Urban Harvest market just two blocks away, many of the hippest restaurants and nightclubs in San Francisco within walking distance and it's affordable housing make this a young and energetic area. As to the homeless and the noise levels, you'll find these anywhere in SF - its not noticeable in the high-rise hotels downtown, but there you'll pay three or four times the amount for a room of the same size. Personally, I love SOMA and am so glad that there is an affordable high quality option here now!Check in was effortless - I received the exact room I booked, a queen bed room on the &quot;courtyard&quot;. This is really a room overlooking the parking lot - don't get any ideas of park benches and trees! But the room was easily accessible and I never had to wait for an elevator (I noticed only one elevator for the main building of the hotel, so I imagine that can cause some waiting from time to time). The lobby is hip and modern - and furnished in reclaimed furniture or furniture made from reclaimed materials. There is a photo booth there where you can have a strip of four photos taken - and a cork wall where you pin up your photos. My room wasn't immediately ready, but I was offered a bottle of water by the clerk as she located a clean room for me.A few minutes later I was in the room - simply furnished, but comfortable for the most part. The bed was made from reclaimed wood, the bedspread from 65% recycled soda bottles (!) and unusable fabrics and there were many other such eco-friendly touches in the room and hotel. The bathroom was small but efficient - and had some very nice touches - there is a bead board wainscoting, which adds an elegant touch to the feel of the room. Nice bright colors and (my favorite aspect of the room) artwork made from reclaimed venetian blinds - with a different scene on each side of the blinds, so one could change the art with the pull of a chain. Very innovative and fun!I ordered room service twice, both times from the hotel's gourmet pizza restaurant - it's well priced (for gourmet pizza) and incredibly good. Very nice food quality (try the potato bacon pizza with gorgonzola sauce) and delivered right to your room.There were a few negatives, but nothing to make me complain to management or to hesitate about staying here again: 1. There was only one outlet visible in the room - and two lamps were plugged into it, making it unusable. I finally located two more outlets - behind the dresser! So I had to pull the dresser out from the wall and reach behind to plug in my laptop. Inconvenient and not thought out.2. Because of the difficulty I had in plugging in my laptop, I charged my cellphone using the bathroom outlet my first night there. And in the morning it was dead: the light switch turns the outlet off in the bathroom, so it died in the middle of the night while I thought it was charging. I plugged it into a wall outlet (with some maneuvering behind the dresser) for the remainder of the trip.3. There is no desk or table of any size in the room - just a tiny side table entirely taken up by a table lamp and a fold-down contraption attached to the wall - at a stand-up height. They provide a stool, but it is constructed of steel rods and terribly uncomfortable when clothed in just gym shorts or some such garment - so one of the bath towels had to be folded into a cushion until it was needed again as a towel!4. And the only coffee service in the room was instant coffee with an electric hotpot. This was surprising in such a hip hotel - they offer upscale amenities (Lather soaps and shampoo) and I would have expected a decent in-room coffee service as well.But these four minor issues are more than mitigated by the location, the affordability and the high quality of the rest of the furnishings and accommodations. This is a true gem and I hope they stay affordable - it's tough to find inexpensive quality accommodations in San Francisco and this is the best I've found yet, and it's eco-friendly to boot!	
